# Fixture (iv): recursive stratum (tc) -> downstream differential
# consumer (marked/flagged), the BUILDFRONTIERS seam.
#
# Batch 1: chain 1->2->3->4 plus a side edge 10->1 (watch node reaching
#   into the chain from outside).
# Batch 2: watch(10) and watch(4) (watch(4) is inside the chain's tail,
#   so flagged(4) requires BOTH marked(4) [tc(10,4) & watch(10)] AND
#   watch(4) itself).
#   At this point tc(10,X) holds for X in {1,2,3,4} (via 10->1->2->3->4),
#   so marked = {1,2,3,4} (all tc-reachable from watched node 10) and
#   flagged = {4} (the only marked node that is ALSO watched).
# Batch 3: retract edge(2,3). This SPLITS the chain: tc(10,X) now only
#   reaches {1,2} (10->1->2), losing tc(10,3) and tc(10,4). marked must
#   shrink to {1,2}; flagged must become EMPTY (node 4 is no longer
#   tc-reachable from the watched node 10, even though watch(4) itself
#   is untouched) -- the downstream consumer's membership is driven
#   PURELY by tc's outDel frontier for stratum-recursive tc rows
#   tc(10,3)/tc(10,4), which a broken BUILDFRONTIERS wiring would fail to
#   propagate (flagged would wrongly still contain 4).
# Batch 4: re-add edge(2,3). tc(10,3)/tc(10,4) must be RE-derived (via
#   tc's own INSERT seed reading edge's outAdd, then tc's own
#   BUILDFRONTIERS outAdd feeding marked's seed again) and flagged must
#   return to {4} -- confirms the seam works in BOTH directions, not just
#   drain.
batch
+ add_edge 1 2
+ add_edge 2 3
+ add_edge 3 4
+ add_edge 10 1
end

batch
+ watch 10
+ watch 4
end

batch
- add_edge 2 3
end

batch
+ add_edge 2 3
end
